  <!-- WHAT IS FLUE CLEANING -->
  <section class="sec">
    <p class="sl">What is it</p>
    <h2>What Is Flue Cleaning — and Why Does It Matter?</h2>
    <p>The flue is the pipe or duct that carries combustion gases from your wood heater or fireplace up and out through the roof. Every time you burn wood, a sticky, tar-like substance called <strong>creosote</strong> condenses on the inside walls of the flue. It builds up with every fire — and left uncleaned, it becomes a serious fire risk.</p>
    <p>Flue cleaning is the process of removing that creosote buildup, along with soot, ash residue, bird nests and any blockages, using a rotary brush that scrubs the full length of the flue from firebox to cap. It restores the flue to a safe, efficient condition.</p>
    <p><strong>Creosote is the leading cause of chimney fires in Australia.</strong> A heavily sooted flue can ignite at temperatures above 250°C — temperatures routinely reached in a wood heater. Chimney fires can exceed 1,000°C, crack liners, spread to roof timbers and cause house fires. Annual flue cleaning is the primary prevention.</p>
    <div class="safety-box">
      <p><strong>Carbon monoxide risk:</strong> A blocked or restricted flue doesn't just cause chimney fires — it can also cause combustion gases including carbon monoxide to back-draft into your home. CO is colourless, odourless and lethal at high concentrations. If you have a wood heater or open fireplace, a CO detector is essential. A clean flue eliminates the risk of CO back-drafting.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

